column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED SMOKING IN UPS FACILITY. DESIGNATED RESPONDER RESPONDED IN FULL PPE EXCEPT HAD SCBA INSTEAD OF GOGGLE. XPO reported that during transit, one or more 55-gallon metal drums containing a flammable ALFAKYD 064W73 were damaged by unknown causes and leaked on to the floor of Trailer#3176569 and on to the parking area upon pulling into the XPO terminal.  XPO determined, after reviewing the BOL, that due to the hazardous class of the material and the volume size, they would immediately contact ERTS and request a contractor.  ERTS has dispatched a contractor on to the site of XPO for clean-up and containment of damaged containers. The contractor confirmed that approximately 1/2 of a gallon of material released from a (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The damaged drum was over packed into a (1) 85-gallon metal drum and the impacted absorbents were placed into a (1) 55-gal metal drum.  No drains or waterways impacted by this spill.

The tank car was reported leaking by UPRR yard employees. Sr. Haz Mat Analyst Tom Robinson was called for a response. The tank car was found to have a loose bottom outlet valve cap and the valve was not making a good seat. The cap was tightened and the gasket replaced. The car is awaiting an OTMA from the FRA to have it brought back to the shipper for unloading.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: On Monday July 2, 2018 around noon (CST), a multi purpose bulk truck driven by an Austin Powder company driver left a customer location in Gainesville, TX, and was heading back to the APC location in Chico, TX (about 60 miles away). The trip is one that the driver made frequently, and the roads he was traveling on were familiar.  The driver is an experienced bulk truck operator, who has been with Austin Powder Company for about two years. The truck was loaded with about 24,000 pounds of bulk oxidizer-3 bins of ammonium nitrate prill, and 1 DOT spec tank filled with ammonium nitrate emulsion.  The truck also had a bulk quantity of combustible liquid, NOS (fuel oil) and a non-bulk quantity of acetic acid.  The road the truck was traveling on (Texas FM 1200) is 2 lanes, running north and south across ranch land. The road climbs slightly at this point, and is straight.  Around 12:05 CST, only two minutes into the trip, as the driver was traveling roughly 58 MPH, the passenger side tires on the vehicle went off the pavement onto a grassy area.   The grass was soggy because of recent rains.  The truck veered off the road for over 200 feet, going nearly 8 feet off the roadway at one point.  The driver attempted to bring the truck back to the roadway, and succeeded in getting both of the steer tires back on the pavement.  However, the weight of the truck had already shifted to the passenger side, and steering back to the left only made the situation worse.  Around 260 feet, the truck began to roll onto its passenger side.  It rolled a complete completely over (360 degrees) and came to rest on its tires completely off the road in a grassy area next to a fence.  It was during this roll that the product leaked out of the ammonium nitrate bins on the vehicle.  A total of between 400 to 500 pounds of ammonium nitrate prill leaked.  Nothing on the bin failed.  Rather the material simply spilled out as the vehicle rolled.  The driver extricated himself from the vehicle, and initiated Austin's emergency response procedures, calling 911, CHEMTREC, and APC personnel.  The driver received superficial bruises, and refused treatment at the scene.  A cleanup crew was dispatched to the scene, and spent roughly 3 hours vacuuming up the spilled product and putting it in 5 drums.  The road was not closed at any time after the accident, or during the cleanup phase.  The crew finished their work and a dig of the impacted area was scheduled for a later date.  During the subsequent interviewing of the driver, he reported seeing "a coyote or a small dog" which caused him to leave the roadway in an effort to avoid hitting the animal.
column169: The driver is re-doing a large portion of his on-the-job training, and completing an online training module prior to getting back to a truck on his own. He has been counseled on safe practices for encountering animals while driving.  Austin is partnering with a  national truck driving school in developing a program for refresher training, which will include rollover prevention.  The training will consist of several hours of classroom training followed by a skills assessment for each driver.  We will begin the program at the Chico, TX location (where the driver in this accident works).

column168: At 0332 ERTS was contacted by Oscar Rodriguez of XPO Logistics UKC about a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading approximately 3 pounds of Ultra yield micronutrients-blue-min zinc powder with sulfur released from a 2000 pound plastic bag. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and it was determined a contractor needed to be sent. The state of California was notified of the release and has given a telephonic report #18-4386. ERTS spoke with Dispatch #7 of the local CUPA as well, but received no report #. Patriot Environmental overpacked the released material and waste material into (3) cubic yard boxes, along with debris and original super sack. No further cleanup is required.

column162: SENIOR VICE PRESIDENT OF TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: Driver was preparing to depart from the Lion Oil Company, 1000 McHenry St., El Dorado, AR. While conducting the pre-trip load inspection, the driver discovered liquid dripping out of the front end of the roll-off container. Driver called the internal Emergency Operations Center to alert of the in-transit release. At this point, the customer was also notified of the spill, and used their own in-house emergency response team to clean up the spill.   A roll-off container trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was in route from the shipper’s location to the designated Clean Harbors disposal facility. During the course of the trip, the driver conducted a routine load check and discovered a small amount of material coming from the roll-off container. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door and contacted his home dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, removed the released material
column169: Investigation of the spill determined the root cause to be the fact that the customer overfilled the roll-off bin. As a result, the customer was counseled and the following suggestions rendered: Load less than ¾ full with this type of material; If box will be sitting more than 2-3 days, add sand or dirt on top of material to act as absorbent in the event of settling or sweating; and, Continue to open tarps and control roll off prior to shipping.   It was determined the roll-off container was leaking due to the presence of free liquid. In order to prevent a recurrence, the initial shipper has been notified of the improper preparation and presence of free liquids in a solid waste stream, the driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Defective Component or Device
column168: A strong odor was observed near UTLX 640530.  Inspection revealed over torqued and unevenly torqued manway bolt nuts, defective manway gasket and a leaking vacuum relief valve.  Vacuum relief valve was removed and replaced with a plug. Manway gasket was replaced and manway properly secured.  Release was estimated at one gallon of vapor and no information is available on the duration of the release.  Shipper will apply for OTMA-2, defect #3.
column169: Shipper will be charged the NAR tariff and has been requested to review loading and inspection procedures with their crews.

column25: Tauber Oil Company by Intercontinental Terminals Co.
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 7/3/18, at approximately 15:00 the PTRC (Portland Terminal Railroad) notified BNSF Vancouver management of a leaking car in their custody.  The GATX 79720 had been identified by ODOT Hazmat Inspector (Ray Hubbell) during a yard inspection as leaking at a rate of approximately 1 gallon per minute from the top of the car.  The Portland Fire Department responded who initiated a road closure on Hwy 30 and instituted a 1/4 mile evacuation of local businesses.  PFD indicated to BNSF that 6 business had employees evacuated and estimated the number evacuated to be approximately 200.  There were no injuries or reported exposures.  BNSF Hazmat responders and contractors responded to the incident.  Upon inspection, the car was found to have an open liquid line valve.  In addition, the male camlock fitting on top of the valve was found to be less than hand tight allowing liquid toluene to lead from the fitting.  Responders were able to close the valve thus stopping the release.  The threaded camlock fitting was removed to have new thread sealant applied.  It was then reapplied to a tool tight condition.  Air monitoring was continuous to monitor for LEL and toxicity via the PID sensor.     Responders on-site estimate that approximately 150 gallons of Toluene was released as a result of the incident.  Most of this liquid quickly evaporated from the car body but some impacts were noted to the ballast immediately underneath the car.  BNSF's environmental contractor obtained soil samples on 7/6/18 from the area under the car to determine toluene concentrations remaining in the soil and to develop a remediation plan.  The times reported and release volumes reported are estimates only and as recieved by different groups in the field.
column169: Tauber Oil Company has been notified of the condition.  The shipper should ensure that post car loading procedures are reviewed with loading personnel.  All valves and fittings should be closed while in transit and threaded connections should be tightened to a tool tight condition.

column168: Car was found by train yard employee and reported a small steady stream leaking from top of car.  BNSF hazmat manager Jeff Hankins responded and found 1 of 4 flange bolts which hold the liquid valve in place to be loose.  Bolt was tightened and others were inspected to ensure tool tight condition.  Car was wiped down and released from hold awaiting OTMA approval to move for unload and repairs.  At least one employee reported an exposure and was taken to nearby hospital for evalu  ation.  Any additional medical is unknown at this time.
column169: Ensure all personnel involved with pre trip inspections account for all fittings, flanges, and other closures to verify road worthiness per DOT and FRA regulations.

column168: Car was noted as leaking in the Casper yard from the BOV. Upon further inspection, the BOV was leaking from where the 4-bolt flange bolts to the bottom of tank car. The tank car had the remaining product removed via a vac truck.
column169: Shipper must ensure that all valves are properly closed tight and that all bolts are tool tightened and in the proper condition for secure transportation to prevent the release of any hazardous materials.

column168: On 07/05/2018 at 1950 hours Jim Pearson, Plant Manager of Fleischmanns Vinegar Company (Car Consignee) discovered NATX300680, a loaded tank car of Ethanol leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the consignee, Fleischmanns Vinegar was the party that reported the incident. Marion Enviromental (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found liquid product to be coming out of the pressure relief valve and liquid product to be coming out of the vapor line valve. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the consignee Jim Pearson at 334-590-1407. Contractor personnel assisted personnel from Fleischmanns Vinegar with offloading product from the car to secure the release.  MEI and Fleischmanns offloaded a portion of the car into drums securing the release.  A special move from CSXT personnel moved the car to the loading rack at the consignee location and Fleischmanns offloaded the car without further incident.  Upon inspection the car revealed 0 inches of outage and was found to be overloaded.  This car was located on a storage track just outside of the consignee facility and was constructively placed on 07/04/18.   NRC notification  1217444   NAR Cause Code: 419 – Overloaded tank   5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80 NARRI    Montgomery, AL – 07/05/18 – NATX300680 – Ethanol

The shipment was transported by Forward Air by Highway from Tampa Fl, to Emirates Airlines Cargo Facility in Orlando, FL on July 27th, 2018.  It was scheduled to be loaded on Emirates passenger flight, EK220/27July from MCO to DXB.  The package was received by Emirates with black shrink wrap covering the hazmat markings on the box.  During security screening at the Emirates Cargo Facility, it was discovered that the package was labelled with a class 9, Miscellaneous Label.  Immediate action taken by screener was to report it to the Air Carrier Management at 11:00 on July 27th.  Once Emirates opened the package, it was discovered that an Airbag Module was contained within the package.  The package was placed on hold at Emirates Cargo Facility in Orlando, MCO International Airport.

column168: GATX 6305 was observed in the BNSF El Paso yard with a leak from the liquid eduction line on 7/4/18. column168: AT 15:02 THE DRIVER KRUMWIEDE ID: 0327459 NOTICED THE BOX WHICH DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS WAS LEAKING INSIDE THEIR PACKAGE CAR. THE BOX WAS THEN PLACED IN A CLEAR PLASTIC BAG AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE LOCKED DMP PROCESSING AREA. THE DMP AREA WAS UNLOCKED AND THE BOX WAS PLACED INSIDE THE DMP AREA AND THEN THE DMP AREA WAS LOCKED AGAIN. LATER AT 17:45 THE DMP AREA WAS UNLOCKED AND THE TWILIGHT DESIGNATED RESPONDER WHO JUST STARTED THEIR SHIFT OPENED THE LEAKING BOX AND NOTICED AN AEROSOL CAN INSIDE THE BOX ALONG WITH SEVERAL WET BOTTLES OF SHAMPOO AND CONDITIONER. THE RESPONDER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE UPS HAZMAT SUPPORT CENTER WHO DETERMINED THAT IT WAS A SUSPECTED UNDECLARED HAZMAT. ONE OF THE SHAMPOO BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP AND ALL THE BOTTLES WERE PACKED FLAT INSIDE THE BOX BECAUSE THEY WERE TOO TALL FOR THE BOX.
column169: PACK ALL LIQUIDS UPRIGHT WITH AT LEAST 2 INCHES OF PADDING ON ALL SIDES AND ENSURE THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX HAS ORIENTATION ARROWS; IN ADDITION, TO ALL NECESSARY HAZMAT MARKINGS.

column168: During routine facility operations, drums were identified as having compromised or lack in proper closures to manufacturers specification. The released material was contained to just the sides of the containers, no water ways, storm drains, land or soil were impacted by this release. In proper personal protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, facility personnel were successful in placing compromised containers into UN rated salvage drums and sent containers onto their final destination without further incident. A courtesy report was called into the Washington Department of Ecology thus generating state reporting number 682848.
column169: Driver was interviewed and it was determined that he rejected 2 containers prior to accepting these into transportation following his thorough container inspections. The Account Manager had a detailed conversation with the generator regarding container selection, proper container closure to manufacturers specification and allowing for head space in each container for shipment. The generator was responsive to the conversation and will ensure their containers are properly closed for transportation.

column168: The driver was traveling north on Ohio River Blvd approaching the intersection of 8th street at approximately 50 MPH when the other party's vehicle traveling south on Ohio River Blvd attempted to make a left onto 8th street into the drivers lane. The vehicles collided on the front passenger side. The hatch on the vehicle came open and two packaging contained radioactive materials were ejected. The packages did not open, the scene was surveyed by local Hazmat and Cardinal Health. No contamination was found, no release of materials occurred.  NOTE that on question 19 I have a nonzero number indicated for the release, but it should be zero because the form will not accept zero for some reason.
column169: This accident occurred through no fault of the drivers. The driver followed his training and responded appropriately to the accident by calling 911 and alerting them to the hazardous materials on board. Additionally, the packages performed as designed by retaining all radioactive materials inside of the packages with zero release of materials.

Freight car NATX 210000 rolled unattended from the Gallup train yard for approximately 1 mile until reaching a mainline rollout protection derail.  Car derailed onto it's side and sheared off the flange/plug assembly on a 2" loading/unloading line allowing product to release at a rate of approximately 30 gals/min.  Cause of rollout is under investigation.  Estimated total loss of product was 20% of the load totally approximately 4,000 gallons to railroad property.  Gallup fire/hazmat team applied a wooden plug/cone to stop the release until the car could be uprighted and transferred.  Environmental remediation is ongoing and includes landfarming soil until neutralization occurs.  Sampling and disposal being conducted per regulations.
column169: Ensure proper securement before leaving equipment unattended.

column168: Inbound truck 8966/ORD arrived in PHL at 1035 Saturday 7/28 with shipment leaking.   AWB# 5312 3346  - 22pcs Description on PPWK: Machine Parts Actual pc that leaked: Heavy Duty Batteries  ¿ At 11:39  I received a call from vendor G2 MOD stating there is a shipment leaking inside inbound truck 8966. ¿ I proceed to the dock door 13 and saw two heavy duty batteries inside the trailer. One of the batteries were laying on the side; I saw wet marking all around the freight inside the trailer. ¿ I quarantine the  dock door to prevent anyone from entering the trailer while I check for the SDS and paperwork . ¿ The description on the paperwork stated machine part, there was no SDS attached. ¿ The customer was contacted for the SDS with no response. ¿ Due to the fact I was unable to obtained the SDS or identified the exact type of battery, I called AA  24hrs Spill Responses for advised. ¿ I was instructed to call an American Airlines contractor, SWS to clean the spill. ¿ SWS Environmental called sub-contractor Miller Environmental who came onsite at 15:30. ¿ Miller Environmental checked the shipment and stated the battery spill acid  inside the trailer. They had to removed and disposed the wooden skid from the shipment.  ¿ Miller Environmental team also stated that the trailer need to be check before reused. Information was pass on the AA trucking. ¿ The cleanup process was completed at 19:45. We reached the SDS from the customer 7/31/18.

The manager quickly informed QA of the situation they had in their area.  QA grabbed a red tote, lined it with a clear hazmat bag and grabbed loose absorb.  They rushed over to the area to investigate the situation.  Upon arrival, they noticed the package in question was an Oxidizer and placed it in the tote.  QA cleaned up the area with the loose absorb and brought the package back to QA placing it in the hazmat processing cage.  New Comments:

Original comments:  Admin was processing an unmarked damaged package that was being returned to Arlington Chemical.  Package contained approximately half liter sized bottles of formaldehyde four of which had burst open.  Upon opening the package the formaldehyde fumes made contact with her right eye causing a burning sensation that would not abate when flushed with water for several minutes.  Called spill vendor who advised that contents could be placed in salvage drum if station personnel were comfortable doing so.  Contents including packaging were placed in salvage drum.  New Comments:

column168: On the afternoon of July 10th, 2018, an incident occurred at Brainerd Chemical during an offload of a 70% trailer. For this offload, a site employee asked for assistance because they were short handed due to vacations, family emergencies and an employee that gave their notice.  The driver volunteered to assist in the offload.  It was the site EE that removed the nuts on the blind flange and there was a small amount of 70% HF that leaked into the containment.  According to the employee the leak was small and contained within the unloading area.  It was allowed to drip to the ground and diluted with water.
column169: Upon return of cargo tank, the 2” valve at the end of the unloading hose was removed and tested by Reliability.  It was tested at 25psi and 55 psi and no breakthrough was observed. No other visual defects were noted when the valve was inspected by Reliability.  Corrective Actions: Test the valve. Replace the hoses with new stainless steel hoses.  Update the unloading SOP to include a walk down of the hose.  Educate all fleet drivers about the incident at next safety meeting.  Reviewed incident with offloading site.

column168: Norfolk Southern employees reported a strong bleach odor near several tank cars while preparing an outbound train for departure.  The employees left the area and Norfolk Southern contacted an emergency response contractor to investigate.  Upon inspection of the train by the contractor, tank car TILX400897 had a leak audible from the ground.  The entry team removed the securement seal from the protective housing and found both liquid line valve and both vapor line valves partially open and all 4 securement plugs loose enough to be turned by hand.  The leak was stopped when the valves were closed.  All four valve handles had to be turned almost 1 full turn to close.  The closure plugs were also tool tightened and the car was released for transportation.

WHEN IT REACHED THE PRELOADER HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID COMING OUT FROM THE CORNER OF THE BOX. HE LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THEN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER PLACED THE PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TUB. THE EQUIPMENT WAS CLEANED UTILIZING THE DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST. column168: Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car UTLX201836 leaking product from the top of the tank.  Upon inspection, the leak was found to be coming from the nipple on the liquid line where the valve threads on.  When the pressure on the tank was relieved the leak stopped.  The valve was tightened on the nipple.  An emergency move was made to return the car to WRB Refining for offloading and certified repair of the car.  The move was about 5 miles.

column168: THE UNLOAD SUPERVISOR CALLED ON THE RADIO STATING THERE WAS A LEAKING PACKAGE IN THE TRAILER AT BAY 14. AFTER I MOVED THE LEAKING PACKAGE TO DMP, I OPENED UP THE PACKAGE TO INSPECT AS WHAT THE CONTENTS ARE PROCEED TO SEARCH MSDS OVER THE INTERNET. AFTER I HAVE BROWSED THROUGH IT, AND DISCOVERED UNDER SECTION 14 OF TRANSPORT INFORMATION. THE PACKAGE IS IN FACT A HAZMAT WHEN BEING TRANSPORT OVER 1 LITER IN THE SHIPMENT UNDER: "UN3266, CORROSIVE LIQUID BASIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S. (SODIUM HYDROXIDE), 8, II." THAT IS WHEN I CONTACTED THE HMSC AND SPOKE WITH DARIAN WHO LATER TOLD ME THIS IS NOT A UNDECLARED HAZMAT BECAUSE THERE IS HAZMAT MARKING ON THE PACKAGE. HOWEVER, WHEN I FIRST DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE "CLASS 8 CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL" WAS ACTUALLY COVERED UP BY SHIPPER. SHE ALSO STATED THAT I SHOULD HOLD THE PKG FOR LOA, AS WELL AS FOLLOW MY DMP PROCEDURES. AFTER THE CALL WITH HER, I CONSULTED WITH MY RMP IN WHICH HE AGREES WITH ME ON PROCESSING AS UNDECLARED IN THE SYSTEM.
column169: AUDIT THE SHIPPER TO PREVENT FURTHER UNDECLARED CORROSIVE SHIPMENTS TO COME THROUGH UPS SYSTEM.

column168: On July 21, 2018, approximately 18:00, at the CSX Radnor Yard in Nashville, TN, it was reported that while train Y29421 was moving south it collided with train Q57620, resulting in the derailment of the lead engine and multiple cars of the Y29421.  As a result of the derailment, car UTLX 640617, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, N.O.S. (Alcohol C12-C16 Poly 1-6 Ethoxylate), sustained damages to the bottom outlet valve which caused the valve’s secondary securement and nozzle assembly to be sheared off as well as caused damaged to, and activation of, the bottom outlet valve’s operating handle.  This resulted in the release of approximately 7,000 gallons of product before CSX response personnel were able to close the valve and stop the release.  The remaining product was tranloaded from the car and transported away from the derailment site by highway tank truck.
column169: (ATTRI code: Derailment cased the bottom outlet valve handle to actuate while being sheared off by the truck set.

column168: During his morning warehouse check, the manager discovered white powder and debris in the back of  the outbound trailer. He then noticed a 36 inch hole in the roof of the trailer. further investigation  confirmed that a 55 gallon, closed head drum containing a styrene, acetone mixture had exploded.  The head of the drum which had exited the trailer was found approximately 90 feet away, still on the  facilities property. Field Service personnel unloaded and decontaminated the trailer. The damaged  drum and associated clean up debris was overpacked and returned to the customer along with the  other 2 drums from this shipment.
column169: Contact with the customer who shipped the drums was initiated to determine what had occurred.  It was discovered that this was not an isolated incident. Ckean Harbors has refused to accept any more  shipments of this material until the customer can assure that no reactions will occur during transport.

column168: WHILE LOADING A TRAILER THE VEOLIA FORKLIFT OPERATOR STRUCK A 55 GALLON DRUM CAUSING A FOUR (4) INCH HOLE IN THE TOP 1/3 OF A 55 GALLON DRUM RELEASING ~3 GALLONS OF MIXED, HALOGENATED SOLVENTS TO THE DOCK AREA. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED INTO A HORIZONTAL POSITION WITH THE HOLE FACING UPWARDS AND LOADING DOCK PERSONNEL PREPARED TO OVER-PACK DAMAGED DRUM. VEOLIA PERSONNEL REPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN 85 GALLON OVER-PACK DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AND CLEANED UP RESIDUAL CHEMICALS ON THE DOCK. AN ESTIMATED 3 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE DRUM, AND THE ENTIRE EVENT LASTED APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES FROM THE TIME OF THE SPILL TO CONCLUSION OF CLEANUP.
column169: VEOLIA HAS RETRAINED THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR AND PERFORMED A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE STAGING FREIGHT ON DOCK FORKLIFT OPERATOR HIT A DRUM ALREADY STAGED ON THE DOCK WITH THE FORK-BLADE ON HIS FORKLIFT CONSEQUENTLY PUNCTURING THE DRUM AND CONTRIBUTING TO THE UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE. spilled MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE PUNCTURED DRUM.
column169: FORKLIFT OPERATORS HAVE TO BE AWARE OF THE CLEARANCES OF THEIR FORKLIFTS TO PREVENT THESE TYPES OF UNINTENTIONAL RELEASES FROM OCCURRING.

column168: The event took place while fueling equipment on a job site. The fuel hose was in a large piece of machinery while the person or persons suppose to be watching the hose looked away. The hose began to spill over and leak fuel for a good 2 minutes plus.   After noticing the diesel fuel was spilling out of the fuel tank we hurried to turn off the tank and begin the cleanup process. The fuel that was on the ground leaked into the manhole. The leftovers were swept away from the manhole and immediately put oil-dry absorbent to clean up the mess from the asphalt.  The fire department was called to the scene to check for pollution. Bay West LLC then took control and put "pillows" at the end of the manhole to absorb the diesel fuel that could pollute the nearby water.

column168: Norfolk Southern Intermodal Ramp personnel reported liquid leaking from IM container OOLU110274.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of a leak was a damaged tote.  The remaining contents of the tote were transferred into a new tote and the load was secured.

During routine facility operations, a container was identified as having released a small portion of its contents. In appropriate protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, facility personnel were successful in placing compromised container into a UN rated salvage drum. Release was contained to concrete only; no land, water ways, soil or storm drains were impacted by this release. A courtesy report to the Washington State Department of Ecology was submitted and state report number 682859 was generated. The container was shipped to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The generator was notified of the compromised container and subsequent release. Generator agreed to be more diligent in container and gasket inspection/selection, as well as of closing containers to manufacturers specifications.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported the odor of ammonia near tank car UTLX954600.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the odor was a vapor leak from the vapor line valve.  The release was the result of the vapor line valve being partially open and the closure plug less than tool tight.

The tank car was reported to have an odor emitting from the top by UPRR yard employees. Sr. Haz Mat Analyst Tom Robinson was called for a response. The tank was found to have a deteriorated man way gasket and one loose man way swingbolt. The gasket was replaced and the swing bolt properly applied. No further remediation was required and the car continued to destination.

During routine facility inspections, a roll-off container staged at the ten-day containment yard was identified as having released some of it contents.  A response team was called in for remediation efforts. In proper personal protective equipment, verified through internal health and safety departments, the response team was successful in remediation of the impacted concrete. The release was contained to the concrete, no soil, water ways, storm drains or land were impacted. The release was reported to the Utah Department of Environmental Quality to Boyd Swenson, who elected to not generate a state report number, as the release was contained and under the report able quantity.
column169: Generator was notified of release and advised of container selection requirements pursuant to waste stream consistency. The profile was suspended pending further movement of waste stream until generator can verify solidification processes of waste streams. Generator and contractor would work towards adjusting their processes prior to offering containers into transportation.

column168: At 1155 ET on 7/27/18 ERTS was contacted by Scott Llewelyn of XPO Logistics in regards to an Unknown Hazardous material leaking outside of the trailer. The caller stated that the shipment has 5 different BOL's and can not determine the product or the amount spilled. ERTS will await Contractor assessment to determine regulatory reporting. ERTS will dispatch a contractor. H2O Environmental has been contacted to respond and perform cleanup activities. At 1430 ET Contractor has arrived on site and located the spill. At nose of trailer. Approximately 20 gallons of product spilled. Need to unload trailer to confirm amount spilled and containers held. 8' x 7' area impacted inside trailer, 4' x 4' area impacted outside the trailer. At 1700 Contractor has completed cleanup. 3 drums of waste generated. Confirmed damage was caused by other cargo crushing the pallet. 4 different products spilled. Contractor reported all products released from the same pallet. Correct PRO #920-733553. ERTS confirmed that the following were damaged (3) 1-gallon steel cans of "Opticolor Lamp Black", (2) 1-gallon steel cans of "Graint One Plus Wiping Stain", (2) 5-gallon pails of "zenith WB Precat Lac-stain" and (11) 1-gallon steel cans of "Neutral tint Paint". The products mixed during the release but was separated as much as possible.
column169: Cargo needs to be loaded in a way that doesn't cause damage
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: On 07/31/2018, at 1315 hours, personnel in the CSXT Ashtabula  Yard discovered GATX 90907, a loaded tank car of Potassium Hydroxide, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, National Response Center, and Ohio EPA were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2018-0731-00222). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a release of less than one gallon of lading from the pressure relief device flange (there was no evidence of PRD lift). The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Ms. Jeanne Kochevar, phone 440-007-6862. Contractor personnel cleaned all visible product from the top of the car, and the car was owner was notified to have a Mobile Repair Unit respond to remove and replace the PRD flange gasket. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. NRC report # 1220050 Cause Code: 422 NARRI: 400
column169: (NAR Code 400)

column168: After loading the railcar, a Veolia employee inadvertently disconnected the hose connection to the railcar without closing the valve.  Approximately 1,000 gallons of waste fuel blend were spilled into the secondary containment before the valve was closed to stop the leak. The spilled waste fuel was collected from the secondary containment.  There was no damage to the railcar.  Please note that Veolia is unable to provide the shipping paper number on this incident report as the shipping paper was not yet created  at this point in time since the material was still being loaded into the railcar.  Creation of the waste shipping paper is the final step in the  pre-transportation phase which had not gotten that far into the pre-shipment process at the time the spill occurred.
column169: The Veolia employee was retrained emphasizing the need for increased awareness to detail of the connection/disconnection process when loading a railcar.

column168: The driver was not driving slow enough for the curved roadway and the load shifted due to a lack of blocking and bracing, causing the truck to turn over.  The wrecker crew unloaded the load that consisted of 10 pallets of car batteries.  It was then determined that approximately 20 gallons of sulfuric acid had been released from the batteries, onto the soil, next to the shoulder of the roadway.  Several caps on top of the batteries had come off causing the acid to release from the batteries.  Excavation of the impacted soil and repair to the area was completed at a later date.
column169: Additional driver training to avoid accidents.  Better blocking and bracing by the shipper to avoid load shift.  Better packaging to prevent caps of batteries from being able to fall out.

column168: There were 3 Passengers were on board the aircraft involved in this incident. Captain Stated that the flight was #1 for take off in the line on the air strip. The FA called the cockpit to report that Passenger Eric Cox had just disclosed that he had some lithium batteries in his valet bag. He had 8 all together, 6 for his drone and 2 e-cigs each the size of a number 2 pencil. Upon hearing Mr. COX report to the FA that he had lithium batteries in his bag, Mr. Nels Long and Mr. Wing KO JR also wanted to report that they also had batteries in their valet bags. It appears that each of these passengers had removed their lithium batteries from their checked bags and placed them in their carry on bags. They were then gate checked at the gate as valet bags. They were provided with an opportunity to remove and liquids, gels, lap tops or anything with lithium batteries or medications along with anything flammable. They left their bags at the end of the jetbridge to be loaded, but said nothing regarding the lithium batteries until they were in line for take off. This caused the flight to return to gate, the ramp had just closed due to lightening. When the A/C parked and the ramp opened, we had these passengers make a positive I.D. of their valet bags and the lithium batteries were removed and were rendered safe for transport, then taken on board with each corresponding passenger. These customers although just prior to take off, self disclosed. The batteries were not confiscated but the customers were allowed to continue on with them when properly secured for transport.

column168: Narrative: On July 31, 2018 at approximately 2233 hours, a single vehicle crash occurred in Denham Springs, LA near the intersection of LA Hwy 1026 (Juban Road) and Crossing Way approximately ¼ mile north of the I-12 intersection with Juban Road. The vehicle involved was a tractor tanker-trailer (Haul of Fame Transport Units TT31 & 9633), with the tanker-trailer containing approximately 9000 gallons of automotive gasoline (HM Class 3, UN #1203). Due to the nature of the crash, the vehicle came to rest on its right side with the tractor’s right-side saddle diesel tank (approx. 100 gallons total capacity) leaking fuel through the fill neck. The diesel fuel (HM Class 3, 1993) spill occurred in the amount of approximately 20-50 gallons and primarily affected the roadway and the grass shoulder and ditch of the southeast quadrant of LA 1026 (Juban Road) and Crossing Way. Haul of Fame Transport, LLC driver, Anthony Reis, called 911 and then notified Haul of Fame Transport President, Boyd Leahy of the crash. Louisiana State Police (LSP), Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality (LADEQ), Livingston Parish Sheriff’s Office (LPSO) and Livingston Parish Fire Department (LPFD) all responded to the scene. OMI Environmental Solutions, LLC 131 Keating Drive Belle Chase, LA 70037 (Ph. 800-645-6671) was contacted as the spill mitigation contractor for clean-up of the scene. Livingston Parish Sheriff’s Office investigated the crash and their investigation revealed that the tractor-trailer was northbound on Juban Road and turned east onto Crossing Way headed to a nearby gas station to deliver fuel when the right-side trailer tires trailed off the roadway and onto the low right side shoulder. The driver stated that in addition to the darkness of the intersection, he was unable to see that the right-side shoulder was low due to tall grass. As the vehicle negotiated the turn, the right-side trailer tires dropped off the right-side edge and with a full load of fuel, the trailer rolled onto its right side. The fifth-wheel connection held, the tractor rolled with the trailer and the tractor-trailer came to rest on its right side on the shoulder of the road. Due to the tractor resting on its right side, the right-side saddle tank, which was full of diesel fuel, leaked from the filler neck cap. The vehicle was equipped with spill mitigation material however, due to the location of the spill being under the overturned vehicle the driver was unable to deploy the material safely. Due to the tanker-trailer containing approximately 9,000 gallons of gasoline, LSP and LPSO closed LA Hwy 1026 (Juban Road) to all traffic both northbound and southbound while the diesel spill was mitigated with sand, socks and mats and the tanker’s contents was removed via pump and hose to another tanker. No fire nor injury resulted from the crash. The tractor and trailer were righted and then removed from the scene by Trading Post Wrecker Service, Denham Springs, LA. The roadway was re-opened at
column169: Corrective actions include the following.  1. The driver involved received remedial training for rollover prevention. Specifically, the FMCSA Cargo Tank Rollover Prevention Training videos were utilized.  The driver completed a written quiz following the presentation to confirm the retention of information.  2. The implementation of a company wide Accident Countermeasures Program to track and institute procedures to prevent crashes. 3. All driver's are to complete the FMCSA Cargo Tank Rollover Prevention Training along with several defensive driving courses targeted to address the following dangerous driving situations; Cornering, Night Driving, Backing, Emergency Maneuvers, Extreme Conditions, Skid Control and General Defensive Driving.

column168: ERTS received a call from David Ondik with ESTES. The caller reported (1) 55 gallon metal drum containing UN1992 released approximately 20 gallons onto the floor of the dock and has begun leaking into the parking lot due to a forklift puncture. The caller stated the terminal personnel have placed absorbents to prevent further migration of the spill. The contractor arrived onsite and confirmed (2) 55 gallon drums were punctured. A total release of 110 gallons of product, 30 gallons of which impacted the parking lot. The contractor used absorbent to clean the release. They completed cleanup and generated (8) 55 gallon metal drums of waste.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car RCRX2067 emitting a vapor cloud from the top of the tank.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the vapor release was coming from the fill hole.  The release was the result of the fill hole lid not sealing properly because the tank liner was damaged in the fill hole tube.  The lading was transferred to another tank car and the shipper was granted an OTMA to move RCRX2067 to shop for repairs.

Arrow material Service is the contract operator of the Norfolk Southern TBT facility in Spartanburg, SC.  Arrow Material personnel were transferring product from tank car UTLX61458 into a Dana Transportation tank truck.  During the product transfer operation product was found leaking from the rear discharge valve on the tank truck.  The leak was the result of the discharge valve on the tank being left open and the cap unsecured.  These issues should have been found and corrected during preload inspection. The valve was closed and the spill contained.  The spilled material was cleaned up and the loading of the tank truck was completed.

column168: There was no package failure, strictly driver/human error. This order was a split delivery within PCA's plant. For the second delivery location, the driver had parked the tractor/trailer at such an angle that prevented all of the product from discharging out of the trailer. When the driver completed, what he thought was the unloading of the rest of the product, he rinsed out the discharge line to ensure that the line was clean. The driver forgor to close the internal valve and when he moved the trailer, the heel (product) left inside the tank drained out in to the discharge line, mixing with the rinse water the driver used to clean the line. Packaging Corp. (PCA) personnel reports the the driver drove the truck to the outside of the plant, stopped and removed the product line cap and allowed rinse water/product mix to spill onto the ground.
column169: The Terminal manager has instructed all drivers to only rinse residual product off product line only in customer's containment area that can be properly collected and disposed of. The Terminal Manager and Regional Trainer will go through all applicable loading and unloading procedures with all terminal drivers to ensure that they are fully competent on those procedures. Regional trainer will also review these procedures with the terminal driver trainers to ensure they properly train new hires before releasing them to deliver these orders. Appropriate disciplinary action will be administered to the offending driver.

column168: On 7/22/2018 at approximately 20:51, the GATX 80210 was found to be leaking a small amount of liquid from the top of the car while in the receiving yard.  The car and area was isolated and BNSF Hazmat responders inspected the car.  It was observed that there was a small amount of liquid coming from the base flange of the liquid line valve.  The responder tightened 4 loose securement nuts on the flange which stopped the leak.  All nuts required approximately 1/2 full rotation to tighten.  The material on the car evaporated and the immediate area was wiped down.  Due to the repair, the shipper obtained an OTMA for further movement to destination and to have repairs inspected and bubble leak tested.
column169: The shipper should review post loading procedures to ensure that processes are in place and followed to inspect and ensure that all fittings and appliances are tool tight and leak free.

column168: At approximately 19:23 on 7/24/2018 the JBHU 282915 was found leaking upon deramp at the BNSF Stockton Intermodal facility.  The slowly leaking container was placed in the haz containment pit for contractor inspection and corrective action.  The contractor responded and inspected the container to find that 4 pails were damaged as a result of a pallet containing the material fell over while in transit.  Approximately 5 gallons in total had spill and was isolated primarily to the container floor.  The spill was neutralized and cleaned up and resecured for shipment.  The recovered material was containerized and left in the container for shipper handling.
column169: Inadequate bracing led to this incident.  Shipper should ensure that all loads are blocked and braced to prevent incidental movement/shifting during transportation.

column168: On 7/25/2018 at approximately 22:00, the residue TILX 257142 was found to be dripping from the BOV cap threads.  The car was isolated and pulled from the train for inspection and repair.  The reporting party reported that approximately 6 drips were noted.  During inspection, it was found that the BOV cap was less than hand tight.  The cap was fully removed to inspect for integrity of the valve.  Material that leaked appeared to be from accumulated residue within the nozzle and cap.  The gasket was inspected and the cap was tool tightened and released to continue in transportation.
column169: The shipper should ensure that appropriate procedures are in place once cars are unloaded to secure and inspect all fittings.  This BOV cap would be tool tightened using a 36" pipe wrench.

WHEN I ARRIVED, I FOLLOWED MY DECISION TREE, RESPONSE SHEETS, AND SINCE THE HAZMAT WAS CORROSIVE THE RESPONSE SHEET INDICATED THAT I PUT ON THE SILVER SHIELD LINERS IN ADDITION TO MY PPE. I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL WEARING MY SILVER SHIELD LINERS, BOOTS, SLEEVES, APRON, GOGGLES, AND NITRILE GLOVES. DISPOSED OF THE PACKAGE FOLLOWING THE "WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR FULL DMP FACILITY". AFTERWARD I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE FOLLOWING THE DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST.

THEN RESPONDER GRABBED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND TRIED TO PUT OUT THE PACKAGE WHICH LOOKED RED - SMOKE/FUMES LOOKED ORANGE, RED, BROWN.
column169: DO NOT USE KLEX-ALL WITH AN OXIDIZER AND PUT CONTENTS IN A SEPARATE BAG WHEN GOING THROUGH THE WASTE DISPOSAL FLOW CHART. CHEMICAL NEEDS TO BE NEUTRALIZED.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 7/26/2018 at approximately 20:00 PST, the GATX 32842 was seen to be releasing liquid spray from the top of the car during coupling in the BNSF Morman Yard (Stockton, CA). One employee in the vicinity reported eye and nostril irritation and was transported to St. Joseph Medical Center in Stockton for evaluation. He was released early in the morning of the 27th with a clean bill of health from the doctor. The car was isolated by 150' in all directions of the car. BNSF Hazmat responders arrived and inspected the car finding that the top of the Salco Rupture disk assembly was missing along with the rupture disk. There were multiple cracks on the assembly noted. The opening was temporarily plugged waiting for replacement parts. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean and neutralize the car and remove any impacted soils. Wastes were properly characterized and prepared for appropriate disposal. The car was repaired by installing a new Salco Tri-vent assembly on 8/3/2018. The car is still on hold pending an approved OTMA for movement to destination for unloading and to complete a bubble leak test.
column169: The shipper should review proper inspection and tightening procedures with employees who handle the Salco assemblies.(NAR:437)

column168: At 1543 ET ERTS was contacted by Mary Davis in regards to a spill of UN1133 adhesive already cleaned up and containerized in (1) 15 gallon steel drum on 7/24/18.  The caller stated that she had no information as to the particulars of the release.  It is unknown if any drains, waterways, or soils were impacted.

During routine facility inspections, a container was identified to have released some of its contents. Facility personnel, in proper personal protective equipment, verified through internal health and safety personnel, were successful in containing the release. An internal response team arrived in appropriate personal protective equipment to transfer the material into UN specification rated containers. No soil, land, waterways or storm drains were impacted by this release; it was contained. The response team was successful in the transfer and the waste went to its final destination without further incident. A courtesy report was submitted to Washington State Department of Ecology resulting in report #682828.
column169: Facility personnel contacted the generator to discuss the release and the process in which the stream is generated. The generator will adjust their processes and container selection for this waste stream.

We will revisit our process assignment with the entire staff and ensure moving forward that all staff are aware of the assigned processors.

column168: On July 26, 2018, at 2005 ET, ERTS was contacted by Landstar Ranger regarding a spill at Stripes Truck Stop in Santo, TX. It was reported that at 1950 ET, the driver arrived at the stop and discovered her trailer leaking an unknown product onto the trailer floor and tractor unit. At 2245 ET, co`ntractors arrived on site and confirmed the product released was (1) 55-gallon steel drum containing UN 1193 "IEB-17". It was reported that there was a pinhole size puncture in the drum resulting in the release of 5-gallons to the trailer floor and asphalt below. Contractors placed volcanic ash on the impacted areas to containerize the waste. The damaged drum was over packed and sent on to the consignee.  On July 27, 2018 at 1235 ET, contractors had completed work and flushed out the trailer with hot water.  All work was complete at 1350 ET. All waste was taken off-site to be disposed of by the contractor.

column17: AEKO KULA DBA ALOHA AIR CARGO
column168: ON 7/10/2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 1300, OUR CREW CHIEF, BRYAN KAM BEGAN THE SECURITY SCREENING PROCESS OF THIS SHIPMENT BY PHYSICALLY SEARCHING EACH PACKAGE. THE NATURE OF GOODS DESCRIBED IS COOKIES. AT APPROXIMATELY 1330, BRYAN CAME TO ME TO REPORT HE SOME DUST OFF CANS IN ONE OF THE PACKAGES AND WANTED TO SEE IF THEY WERE CONSIDERED DANGEROUS GOODS AS HE WAS UNSURE. HE BROUGHT ME THE PACKAGE THAT HELD THE CANS. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE CANS, I SEEN THAT A DOT SPECIAL PERMIT WAS PRINTED ON THE CAN. THE NUMBER IS DOT SP-11516. I PULLED-UP THE SPECIAL PERMIT ON THE PHMSA WEBSITE AND UPON READING THIS SP, I DISCOVERED THE FOLLOWING: 1) THE CANS MUST BE SHIPPED CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY. THIS SHIPMENT WAS STATED TO GO ON A PASSENGER AIRCRAFT. 2) NO SHIPPING PAPERS WERE OFFERED FOR TRANSPORT 3) THERE IS NO MARKS OR LABELS ON THE PACKAGE TO INDICATE A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT 4) THERE IS NO DOT SP MARKING ON THE PACKAGE AS WELL 5) A COPY OF THE SPECIAL PERMIT WAS NOT PROVIDED AT THE SAME TIME OF TENDER I THEN PROCEEDED TO CALL FAA HAZMAT INSPECTOR, PEARL BELLO WHO ADVISED ME TO COMPLETE AND SUBMIT THIS FORM. PICTURES OF THE OUTSIDE AND INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE WERE TAKEN AND SENT TO PEARL AND HAVE BEEN SUBMITTED WITH THE REPORT AS WELL.  INSPECTION OF ALL PACKAGES WAS COMPLETED ON 7/11/18 AT APPROX. 0800. NO OTHER DANGEROUS GOODS ITEMS WERE FOUND. SPOKE WITH PEARL AND SHE ADVISED TO REMOVE THE DUST OFF AND SHIPMENT CAN PROCEED TO LAS FOR DELIVERY.

column168: Hawaiian Airlines (HA) accepted a shipment identified by the Air Way Bill (AWB) 173-91977152 and tendered for transport on HA15 28JUL2018.  The shipment contained DG and the proper paper work was completed for  the shipment including the shipper's declaration and Notification to the Pilot in Command (NOPIC).  Once the shipment was loaded the and the jet bridge was detached from the aircraft, the Load Master (LM) realized that he had forgotten to provide the pilot with the NOPIC. The LM called the pilot to inform him that the NOPIC needed to be signed. The pilot declined to have the jet bridge reattached and asked the LM to provide the information over the radio and send a copy of the NOPIC to dispatch. The flight departed at approximately 1015.  Root Cause of the incident was that the Company's policy on the acceptance and handling of dangerous goods was not properly followed.  It is the policy in the Flight Ops Manual 16.2.2 (G) of Hawaiian Airlines that for any Hazmat loaded on the aircraft, the Captain will be notified of the article by a NOPIC and the NOPIC must be on the flight deck whenever there is Hazmat on the aircraft. Per CFR 173.33(11)(b),  a copy of the NOPIC needs to be maintained on board during the transport of hazard material aboard the aircraft.  According to 49 CFR 175.33 - Shipping paper and notification of pilot-in-command: The NOPIC document (HAL 902) must be presented to the PIC for signature and carried onboard the aircraft for the duration of the flight. HA Passenger Service Manual Section 10.0 also states that the completed NOPIC must be presented to the PIC once the hazmat has been loaded. There was no failure of the package.
column169: The PIC was counseled by the Chief Pilot and Flight OPs has reviewed training to ensure that  continuous qualification ground school courses provide adequate training for DG awareness.     Station Chief for the flight and all agents received a Letter of Counseling for not being aware of the regulations and  HA policies. All applicable personal at the SAN station were re-briefed on the NOPIC requirements and  procedures and company policies and requirements were reviewed with all responsible personnel.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release. .'J
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material. >

column168: ON 7/9/2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS TWO IMTT OPERATORS WERE LOADING ALL CHEM TRAILER #AL858 WITH METHANOL. AT APPROXIMATELY 1505 HOURS THE TRUCK WAS DONE LOADING. THE IMTT OPERATORS STARTED BLOWING BACK THE PRODUCT LINE TO THE TRUCK. ONE OF THE IMTT OPERATORS NOTICED THERE WAS A SLIGHT DRIP COMING FROM THE GASKET AT THE FLANGE ON THE TRAILER. THE TWO IMTT OPERATORS NOTIFIED THEIR SUPERVISOR AND ATTEMPTED TO GET THE LOADING TUBE TO STOP LEAKING AT THE FLANGE. ONCE THEY DETERMINED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE WOULD NOT HOLD, THE IMTT SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE IMTT CHEMICAL OPERATIONS MANAGER TO COME TO THE LOADING RACK TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION. THE IMTT CHEMICAL OPERATIONS MANAGER FOR US ECOLOGY (IMTT’S OSRO) TO TRANS LOAD FROM ALL CHEM TRAILER TO A US ECOLOGY VACUUM TRUCK. IT WAS NOTED THERE IS A 4TH CAP WITH A VALVE ON THE TRAILER OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE LOADING VALVE. THE IMTT CHEMICAL OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR AND THE US ECOLOGY FOREMAN WERE GETTING READY TO TRANSFER THE LOAD FROM THE TRUCK TRAILER. WHEN THEY RELEASED THE CAP ON THE TRUCK THERE WAS A TREMENDOUS AMOUNT OF PRESSURE WHICH RELEASED APPROXIMATELY. 40-50 GALLONS OF METHANOL INTO THE SURROUNDING SCALE CONTAINMENT AT THE LOADING RACK. IMTT’S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM IMMEDIATELY RELEASED FOAM TO SUPPRESS THE METHANOL RELEASE. ONCE THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED US ECOLOGY CONTINUED WITH TRANS LOAD. THE BALANCE OF THE METHANOL WAS THEN TRANSFERRED FROM THE US ECOLOGY TRUCK TO ANOTHER ALL CHEM TRAILER.
column169: UPON FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT AN OBSTRUCTION WAS LODGED INSIDE THE TRAILER’S INTERNAL VALVE THAT PREVENTED PROPER CLOSURE. IMTT CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER OF THE PRODUCT BEING LOADED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. ANY COSTS INCURRED FOR THE CLEANUP RESPONSE AND REPAIRS TO THE TRAILER BE HANDLED BY THE CUSTOMER AND THE TRANSPORTATION COMPANY.

column168: Tank trailer was in the process of being unloaded. Driver advised that he connected the hoses and fittings in preparation for unloading. The facility began the unloading process by pumping the load from the tanker. Approximately 30 minutes into the unloading process the tanker failed and caused a release of product from the side of the tanker. Investigation indicates that one of the primary contributing factors to the tank failure is that the vapor recovery valve was closed which led to a vacuum being created during the process of pumping the load from the tanker. Secondary to this would be that the vacuum relief valve did not engage properly to relieve vacuum from the tanker. Local fire department responded initially to the spill followed up by an emergency response team to complete the cleanup and remediation.

column168: At 2318 ET, ERTS received a call from Earl Coggins with Landstar. The caller reported that an unknown material, possibly hazardous, has released inside the trailer of trailer #691767 caused by a hard break which resulted in a drum falling off of a pallet and releasing an unknown amount onto the trailer floor and the asphalt roadway. At 0543 ET, Contractor reports the leaked material is sodium hydroxide solutions per the 275-gallon poly tote. The tote released approximately 20 gallons to the trailer floor and 5 gallons to asphalt below. The contractor neutralized the spill using citric acid solution (pH 8) and transferred damaged drum. Two cardboard drums were considered waste after clean and the waste was over-packed. A total of 197 gallons of product was transferred to a new tote. There was a total of 7 waste drums. There is no further cleanup necessary.

column168: On 7/9/18 at approximately 1400 hours two IMTT Operators were loading All Chem trailer#AL858 with methanol. At approximately 1505 hours the truck was done loading. The IMTT Operators started blowing back the product line. to the truck. One of the IMTT Operators noticed there was a slight drip coming from the gasket at the flange on the trailer. The two IMTT Operators notified their supervisor and attempted to get the loading tube to stop leaking at the flange. Once they determined that the internal valve would not hold, the IMTT Supervisor notified the IMTT Chemical Operations Manager to come to the loading rack to evaluate the situation. The IMTT Chemical Operations Manager for US Ecology(IMTT's OSRO) to trans load from All Chem trailer to a US Ecology Vacuum truck. It was noted there is a 4" cap with a valve on the trailer opposite side of the loading valve. The IMTT Chemical Operations Supervisor and the US Ecology Foreman were getting ready to transfer the load from the truck trailer. When they released the cap on the truck there was a tremendous amount of pressure which released approximately. 40-50 gallons of methanol into the surrounding scale containment at the loading rack. IMTT's Emergency Response Team immediately released foam to suppress the methanol release. Once the release was contained US Ecology continued with trans load. The balance of the methanol was then transferred from the US Ecology truck to another All Chem trailer.
column169: Upon further inspection it was discovered that an obstruction was lodged inside the trailers internal valve that prevented proper closure. IMTT contacted the customer of the product being loaded to report the incident. column168: Original comments:  ON TUESDAY JULY 31 AT 1030am the box was put on the nc belt that feeds the van line to be loaded for morning delivery when it was dropped. It became apparent that the containers inside were leaking when the box started showing signs of being wet. The box was immediately put inside a salvage drum. There was no liquid spilled on any other boxes or property and it must of spilled about a cups worth of liquid inside the box. Note this hazmat is a solid mixture I don't know it spilled at all, but I have pictures. Upon further inspection of the box I noticed one cap was missing form one container most likely caused by the fall, I could not find the cap. The caps on two other containers were loose and had visible signs of liquid seeping out the tops. The outer box has visible signs of damage where the product ate away at the box. Full safety gear was used to segregate and store the damaged hazmat till it was put inside the drum. The package is currently inside a salvage drum inside the hazmat cage where it awaits a disposition from PGH for disposal.  New Comments:
Associate did not block and/or brace freight properly for transport.  Freight was crushed causing release of product.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 15:45 ON 12 JULY 2018, AN EMPLOYEE WAS INJURED AFTER BEING SPRAYED BY 60% CHRONIC ACID SOLUTION. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS AT OUR FACILITY. WE RECEIVE THE MATERIAL AS CHROMIC FLAKES FROM ELEMENTIS AND THEN ADD WATER DIRECTLY TO THE RAILCAR TO MAKE IT A 60% CHROMIN ACID SOLUTION THAT WE USE IN ONE OF OUR PROCESSES. THE EMPLOYEE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF ATTACHING A HOSE TO THE DISCHARGE FLANGE TO UNLOAD THE 60% CHROMIC ACID SOLUTION TO THE CHROMIC ACID STORAGE TANK. WHEN HE REMOVED THE CAP, THE MATERIAL SPRAYED OUT THE BOTTOM VALVE SPRAYING THE EMPLOYEE WITH 60% CHROMIC ACID. TWO EMPLOYEES ATTEMPTED TO OPERATE THE VALAVE TO STOP THE SPRAYING, HOWEVER THEY WERE UNSUCCESSFUL IN STOPPING THE SPRAY AFTER CYCLING THE VALVE A NUMBER OF TIMES. WE MONITORED THE SPILL FOR A PERIOD OF THREE HOURS AS 9,608 GALLONS OF 60% CHROMIC ACID SOLUTION WENT TO CONTAINMENT. WE WERE ABLE TO PUMP THE MATERIAL TO TWO PROCESS WATER TANKS IN THE TANK FARM TO REUSE. AFTER THE RAILCAR WAS EMPTIED WE INVESTIGATED TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE VALVE NOT OPERATING. WE FOUND THAT THE REACH ROD WAS NOT CONNECTED TO THE BOTTOM DISCHARGE VALVE. WE ALSO DETERMINED THAT THE INJURED EMPLOYEE NEVER UNPINNED THE VALVE AND THE VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED-PINNED POSITION AS IT ARRIVED FROM THE VENDOR. THIS WAS ALSO VERIFIED WITH THE TWO EMPLOYEES WHO ATTEMPTED TO OPERATE THE VALVE; THE VALVE ARRIVED IN THE PINNED CLOSED POSITION, ROD WAS DISENGAGED FROM VALVE, AND THE VALVE WAS DETERMINED TO BE PARTIALLY OPENED ALLOWING MATERIAL TO PASS THROUGH. THE RAILCARS THAT DELIVER CHROMIUM TRIOXIDE TO THE SITE HAVE TWO COMPARTMENTS. THE FIRST COMPARTMENT HAD ALREADY BEEN UNLOADED EARLIER WITH NO ISSUES-THIS ROD HAD A MECHANICAL STOP THAT PREVENTED THE ROD FROM BECOMING DISENGAGED FROM THE VALVE. THE SECOND COMPARTMENT DID NOT HAVE A MECHANICAL STOP THUS ALLOWING THE ROD TO BECOME DISENGAGED FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE.
column169: WE CONTACTED OUR VENDOR AND DISCUSSED WITH THEM THE ISSUES WE FOUND WITH THE RAILCAR AND RESULTED IN THE INJURY AND RELEASE OF MATERIAL. THEY DID COME ON-SITE TO INVESTIGATE AND DETERMINE THEY NEEDED TO REPLACE THE VALVE BEFORE SHIPPING BACK TO THEIR FACILITY. THEY SENT A LICENSED CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE VALAVE A COUPLE OF DAYS FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT AND WE WERE ABLE TO SEND THE RAILCAR BACK TO ELEMENTS. THEY ASSURED US THAT THEY DO PRE AND POST INSPECTIONS ON ALL OF THEIR RAILCARS AND IT IS THEIR INTENTION THAT THE VALVE IS CLOSED BEFORE BEING SHIPPED OUT. THEY ARE CONDUCTING AN INTERNAL REVIEW OF THEIR INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS. OUR SITE HAS IMPROVED OUR OPERATING IN RESPONSE TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: It was initially reported a release of 20 gallons of gasoline had been released from the discharge hose when disconnecting. The fuel impacted the concrete and then traveled to the roadway and possibly a storm drain. The fire department and Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality(ODEQ) have been contacted and were onsite. The gasoline had impacted a storm drain that led to and out fall to a creek. The fuel had been contained to the storm drain. The road way had an area approximately 20 feet by 40 feet that was impacted. There was also a long narrow trail leading back to the initial release location. Mr. Girard inspected two(2) storm drains which could not be opened to check for gasoline. One drain had a gallon or so of gasoline inside it. The only collection point was the outfall of the storm drain. The team placed absorbent boom and the fire department flushed the drain with 1500 gallons of water. The team collected 2,500 gallons of water. Very little gasoline was on the water. The team generated two(2) 55 gallon drums of spent absorbents from cleaning the impacted roadway. ODEQ was still concerned that the fuel did not make it completely out of the storm drain system. Mr. Girard suggested a team return in the morning and enter the large concrete culvert and utilize absorbent boom to collect and draw any remaining fuel out. Mr. Lance Pennington of ODEQ agreed with the plan. Monday- July 16,2018 The following morning the team returned and implemented the plan. Very little fuel was located in the back of the culvert. This was drawn out with boom and soaked up by absorbent pads. The team replaced the existing boom and pads and left them in place to be picked up at a later date. The team generated two(2) bags of spent absorbents. Friday- July 20,2018
column169: Proper training for driver to ensure all valves are closed and that any remaining fuel in hoses are to be properly drained before disconnecting.

column168: Driver was traveling east on a rural road near Yukon, OK at 46mph. The driver took his eyes oil the road momentarily and the truck's passenger side tires left the pavement. The roadway had no shoulder and a steep embankment existed. The driver attempted to correct the truck back on the roadway, but was unable to do so causing the transport to roll onto it's side. The cargo tank trailer was carrying 7000 gallons of diesel fuel which began slowly leaking from the manway hatches of the compartments and vent as a result of the accident. Approximately 150 gallons of fuel leaked out of the cargo tank over roughly a three hour period. Emergency responders were able to capture much of the leaking fuel by means of a tarp. The fuel remaining in the wrecked cargo tank was successfully transferred to another truck. The wrecked truck and trailer were then uprighted and towed away from the scene. An Environmental Contractor excavated a small area where fuel had impacted soil, and then backfilled and reseeded. No long term effects are expected.

column168: On 7/26/18 at approximately 09:30 am IMTT was in the process of loading a Langer Transportation trailer with Butyl Acrylate. After loading approximately 5,975 gallons the IMTT Chemical Operator noticed a small drip of product dripping from the side of the trailer. The IMTT Chemical Operator contacted his supervisor who reported to the area. The IMTT Chemical Operator and Supervisor conducted an investigation and found the leak coming from a small hole in the body of the trailer. The IMTT Chemical Operator placed a pan under the drip and added Neutralizer to the pan to mitigate the odor.
column169: IMTT contacted the customer of the product (Butyl Acrylate) who requested that contents of the trailer be pumped back into the original above ground storage tank. After the transfer was complete the IMTT Chemical Supervisor checked inside of the trailer to make sure there was no residual remaining. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor then called US Ecology(IMTT's OSRO) to clean the affected area on the surface of the trailer. Any costs incurred for the cleanup response and repairs to the trailer will be handled by the customer.

column168: On 7/31/18 at approximately 10:15 pm an IMTTChemical Operator had just completed loading of methanol into a railcar when he noticed product overflowing out of the top hatch. The IMTT Chemical Operator contacted his supervisor to report the incident. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor went to the rail car and noticed that there was methanol running down the side of the railcar. Upon further investigation it was noticed that the product(methanol) was all the way up to the top of the.fitting on the 3" induction tube and the vapor line was closed with pressure still on the line. The IMTT Chemical Supervisor started to relieve the pressure on the vapor line and at that point the product started to go down the induction tube.
column169: Upon investigation it was determined that the IMTT Chemical Operator failed to relieve the pressure in the hose before disconnecting the rail car. This would have allowed all the methanol to fully drain from the hose into the rail car. The Operator was instructed by his supervisor on the the proper procedure. The rail car was secured and transported without further incident.

column168: ON 07-12-18, A COMPANY DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON KY 754. FOR REASONS UNKNOWN, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF TRACTOR 1202 TO MERGE OFF OF THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. IN AN ATTEMPT TO REGAIN CONTROL, IT APPEARS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STEER THE TRACTOR BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY. THE EVIDENCE SUGGESTS THE DRIVER OVERCORRECTED WHICH CAUSED THE WEIGHT OF THE VEHICLE & LOAD TO SHIFT OVERTURNING THE TRACTOR / TRAILER COMBINATION. THE TANK WAS LOADED WITH 4600 GALLONS OF BLEACH, APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS ESCAPED DUE TO A DAMAGED VALVE ON THE TOP, REAR OF TANK 717.   I ARRIVED ON SCENE BEFORE PECCO ENVIRONMENTAL, TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT, I PLACED BOOMS AND SPILL PADS AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND THE FRONT OF THE TRACTOR.  THE NEAREST DRAIN WAS APPROXIMATELY 500 FEET WEST OF THE TRACTOR. THE PRODUCT DID NOT CONTAMINATE ANY BODY OF WATER NOR DID IT ENTER ANY DRAINS.  WHEN PECCO ARRIVED, THEY USED A BOBCAT TO CREATE A BERM ON BOTH THE FRONT AND REAR OF THE UNIT AS AN ADDITIONAL CONTAINMENT EFFORT.
column169: THIS COLLISION IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION, WE WILL HOWEVER CONDUCT ROLLOVER AWARENESS TRAINING IN THE UPCOMING SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: At 0158 ERTS was notified by Kyle Green of XPO Logistics of a 4oz release of on UN1791 Hypochlorite solution, with more than 5% available Chlorine from a 55gal drum on trailer 3195210 . The cause was due to a loose cap. The product landed on the leg of a terminal working who went to the hospital for treatment. Prior to leaving for the hospital the terminal called the XPO injury hotline who couldn't respond due to being "too busy", as per Kyle Green. ERTS notified the NRC. Mr. Threatt issued report number 1218587. ERTS reported the spill to the state. Phil issued report number 2018-4384. 0415 Contractor arrived on site and stated that the bung cap was lose. Contractor tighten the cap and wiped the drum clean. No waste was generated from this alert. Contractor departed site at 0435.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE FAILED TO PROPERLY VENT THE STORAGE TANK. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR DISPATCHED BY THE CUSTOMER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.

column168: Manuel Ventura with Roadrunner Transportation Services called ERTS in regard to a strong odor coming from his trailer. He is unsure of the material that was released or where it is coming from. Manuel requested a team to respond to locate the released material, clean the impacted area, containerize the waste and take it off site. Manuel stated he doesn't see anything leaking from the trailer. It was confirmed once a spill team arrived onsite that 1-5 gallon metal container of Ethyl Ester was damaged and was evaporating product. They were also able to identify that 2-1 gallon poly jugs of ethyl alcohol were damaged and evaporating product. All damaged containers were overpacked and containerized for disposal.

column168: DRIVER HAD JUST LOADED GASOLINE AND DIESEL (FOR DELIVERY TO A RETAIL GAS STATION) AT THE MOTIVA KENNER TERMINAL. HE WAS ENTERING I-10 AT WILLIAMS HEADING EAST TOWARD THE CAUSEWAY INTO COVINGTON. AS HE WAS THE ENTRANCE RAMP, EITHER THE TRAILER TIRE, AXLE OR AIRBAG FAILED, CAUSING TOTAL FAILURE OF ALL 3 COMPONENTS. THAT RESULTED IN THE TRAILER BOBBLING AND COMING IN CONTACT WITH CONCRETE ABUTMENT ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THAT CONTACT PIERCED 1 OF THE 5 COMPARTMENTS IN THE TRAILER, ABOUT 1/3 OF THE WAY UP, WHICH CONTAINED 2,362 GALLONS OF UNLEADED 10% ETHANOL GASOLINE. THE DRIVER MAINTAINED CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, THEN HE NOTIFIED US. WE CALLED OMI WITHIN A FEW MINUTES AND THEY WERE ON SITE WITHIN AN HOUR. THEY IMMEDIATELY COLLECTED AS MUCH FUEL AS THEY COULD IN DRUMS AND REMOVED THE FUEL THAT HAD ALREADY SPILLED. A SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL REACHED THE DRAINAGE CANAL ON THE SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE. OMI WAS ABLE TO BLOCK THAT FUEL FROM SPREADING AND COLLECT IT. APPROXIMATELY 1,400-1,500 GALLONS OF FUEL SPILLED ONTO THE INTERSTATE. SEVERAL HUNDRED GALLONS WERE RECOVERED IN DRUMS AND 600 GALLONS REMAINED IN THE COMPARTMENT. OMI WORKED UNTIL LATE THAT EVENING AND CAME BACK EARLY THE NEXT MORNING FOR THE FINAL CLEANUP. THEY WERE COMPLETELY FINISHED THE CLEANUP PROJECT BEFORE NOON THE NEXT DAY. IT TOOK US APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS TO GET ANOTHER FUEL TRUCK ONSITE, REMOVE THE REMAINING FUEL FROM THE TRAILER, AND TOW IT AWAY FROM THE SITE. THE STATE POLICE HAD THE AREA ROADWAYS CLOSED ALMOST IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT UNTIL APPROXIMATELY 19:05.
column169: THE INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY EQUIPMENT FAILURE. IT WAS UNAVOIDABLE IN THE RESPECT THAT ALL OF OUR EQUIPMENT IS MAINTAINED REGULARLY AND THIS FAILURE COULD NOT HAVE BEEN ANTICIPATED. AS FAR AS THE DRIVER REACTION TO THE INCIDENT, HE PERFORMED ADMIRABLY BY MAINTAINING CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, AVOIDING A ROLLOVER AVOIDING CONTACT WITH ANY OTHER PERSONS OR VEHICLES, AND CONTACTING THE PROPER AUTHORITIES IMMEDIATELY. THE MANAGEMENT OF LAVIGNE LOGISTICS RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY BY CONTACTING OMI, OUR EMERGENCY CLEANUP VENDOR. IN ADDITION, WE WERE ABLE TO CONTACT A LOCAL TRANSPORT COMPANY TO GET TO OUR TRUCK PUMP OUT THE REMAINING FUEL SO THAT IT COULD BE TOWED, AND THEY ARRIVED VERY QUICKLY IN SPRITE OF THE ROADWAY CLOSURES.

THE RAILCAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND 67 MPH ON SR-6, (4 LANE DIVIDED HWY) ENTERING A CONSTRUCTION ZONE WITH 65 MPH SPEED LIMIT WHERE 2 LANES WERE MERGING INTO ONE, (LEFT LANE INTO RIGHT LANE). AFTER CONSTRUCTION BARRELS MOVED DRIVER INTO RIGHT LANE, BARRELS SHIFTED HIM BACK TO LEFT LANE AND INTO LEFT TURN LANE IN CONSTRUCTION AREA. THE BARRELS THEN APPARENTLY SHIFTED TRAFFIC BACK ACROSS 3 LANES TO THE FARTHEST RIGHT LANE AT WHICH POINT DRIVER BECAME CONFUSED AT WHERE CONSTRUCTION BARRELS WERE DIRECTING HIM.  HE FOLLOWED WHAT HE THAT WAS THE CORRECT PATH IN THE MIDDLE WHICH HE SOON REALIZED WAS RIGHT INTO THE RIVER BENEATH THE BRIDGE. AT THIS POINT DRIVER TO EVASIVE MANEUVERS TO AVOID DROP-OFF INTO THE RIVER AND SWERVED LEFT WHERE HE MADE CONTACT WITH JERSEY BARRIERS SNAPPING HIS STEER AXLE, PUNCTURING HIS LEAD TRAILER AND OVERTURNING BOTH TRAILERS WHILE THE TRACTOR STAY UPRIGHT CRASHING INTO BARRIERS ON BOTH SIDES OF THE BRIDGE OVER THE RIVER. AT THIS POINT CRUDE OIL BEGAN SPILLING RON THE PUNCTURED BACK COMPARTMENT OF HIS LEAD TRAILER FROM A GASH OF 2"-4" HIGH BY 20" WIDE. APPROXIMATELY 4,000 BARRELS SPILLED MAINLY CONTAINED TO BRIDGE SURFACE AND SOME GETTING INTO STORM DRAIN THAT LED TO THE RIVER BELOW.  DRIVER HAS SUSTAINED INJURIES TO HIS SHOULDER AND RIBS WAND WAS DISORIENTED. EMERGENCY CREWS ARRIVED AND ATTENDED TO DRIVER AND BEGAN PUTTING A BURM AROUND THE STORM DRAIN THAT LED TO THE PRICE RIVER BELOW TO STOP ANY FURTHER SPREAD OF CRUDE OIL AND CONTAINED IT UNTIL MORE HAZMAT CREWS ARRIVED AND COULD BEGAN THE CLEANUP AND RECOVERY PROCESS.
column169: SPEED LIMIT THROUGH THE CONSTRUCTION ZONE NEEDS TO BE REDUCED FROM THE 65 MPH. THE PLAN FOR THE CONSTRUCTION BARRELS WAS RIDICULOUS AND VERY CONFUSING TO ANYONE WHO DROVE THROUGH THE AREA, ESPECIALLY IN THE DARK. NOT 24 HOURS LATER AFTER ROADWAYS HAD BEEN CLEARED AND WAS OPEN A PICKUP TRUCK TO THE EXACT SAME ROUTE EXCEPT FAILED TO SWERVE AND ROLLED HIS PICKUP TRUCK INTO THE RIVER NEARLY KILLING HIM. AT THIS POINT, LAW ENFORCEMENT REQUESTED THE CONSTRUCTION COMPANY AND DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION REVISIT HOW THE BARRELS WERE LAID OUT.  THE MOST OBVIOUS PROBLEM HERE WAS THE CONSTRUCTION BARREL THAT WERE SETUP AND THE PLAN NAVIGATING TRAFFIC. BASED ON SOCIAL MEDIA POSTS THERE WERE SEVERAL OTHER NEAR MISSES AT THE SAME LOCATION DAYS BEFORE LEADING UP TO THE TWO ACCIDENTS.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A TOTE FELL FROM THE TRUCK, WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS OF LIQUID FERTILIZER. THE FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY AND ADJACENT ROADSIDE DITCH. THE RURAL METRO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE, AND PROCEEDED TO WASH THE PRODUCT FROM THE ROADWAY INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH. KARY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSESS THE SITE.   PIMA COUNTY DEQ RESPONDED TO PERFORM A SITE ASSESSMENT AND REQUESTED ADDITIONAL RESPONSE. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. RESPONDED TO THE SITE, RECOVERED VISUAL CONTAMINATION WITHIN THE FREE STANDING WATER IN DITCH, AND SITE WAS DEEMED FOR CLOSURE. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
