column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING PROPANE DELIVERIES. IN BETWEEN DELIVERIES, WHILE DRIVING FROM ONE STOP TO THE NEXT, PROPANE BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER SPOKE WITH COMPANY OWNER, PARKED IN SAFEST PLACE POSSIBLE AND CONTRACTED 911. DRIVER EVACUATED THE TRUCK AND THE STREET AROUND WHERE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED. POLICE AND EMS BLOCKED THE ROAD AND EVACUATED HOMES CLOSE TO THE TRUCK. POLICE AND EMS CUT POWER TO THE HOMES CLOSE TO THE TRUCK. EMS CONTACTED VIRGINIA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT. VA EMS TOOK OVER THE SCENE AND CONTACTED NN HAZMAT TEAM. WE ATTEMPTED TO PUMP THE TANK BUT WERE UNABLE TO DO SO DUE TO LACK OF PRESSURE IN THE VESSEL. WE RELOCATED THE TRUCK TO AN OPEN AREA APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES AWAY. WE ATTEMPTED TO PUMP THE TANK BUT WERE UNABLE TO DO SO DUE TO LACK OF PRESSURE IN THE VESSEL. WE CONTACTED THE AUTHORIZED SERVICE CENTER WHO HANDLES OUR PROPANE TRUCK INSPECTIONS AND REPAIRS. THEIR MECHANIC CAME TO THE SCENE, REMOVED THE RELIEF VALVE AND PLUGGED THE TOP OF THE TANK. WE DELIVERED THE TRUCK TO THE AUTHORIZED SERVICE CENTER FOR INVESTIGATION AND IT WAS DEEMED THAT HE BAFFLE HIT THE BOTTOM OF THE RELIEF VALVE CAUSING IT TO  BLOW APART, RESULTING IN THE LEAK.
column169: INCIDENT WAS UNPREVENTABLE. TRUCK AND TANK HAVE HAD ALL REQUIRED INSPECTIONS.

column168: ON 7/9/2018, FEDEX DRIVER RONALD PIETRAMALA, WAS TRAVELING WEST ON HWY 420. RONALD STATED THAT HE WAS LOOKING AT HIS DELIVERY DEVICE AND FAILED TO SEE OR STOP AT THE STOP SIGN OF INTERSECTION 178/420. TEAM LOGISTICS DRIVER GREG BURTON, WAS TRAVELING SOUTH  ON 178 AND T-BONED THE FEDEX VAN, CAUSING HIS TRACTOR TRAILER TO ROLL ON IT'S SIDE. GREG WAS TRAVELING AT 55 MPH AND SLOWED HIS VEHICLE TO 38 MPH BEFORE IMPACT. AFTER SLIDING APPROXIMATELY 75 YARDS, THE TRAILER FLIPPED COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN IN THE MIDDLE OF HWY 178. GREG WAS ABLE TO PUSH T HE FRONT WINDSHIELD OUT AND EXIT VEHICLE. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TOTALED DUE TO ACCIDENT. THE TRAILER HAD TWO COMPARTMENTS THAT WERE BREACHED, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 2,582 GALLONS OF ETHANOL TO LEAK FROM TRAILER. THE FEDEX VAN WAS PUSHED INTO THE WOODS ACROSS THE INTERSECTION. NEITHER DRIVER SUSTAINED LIFE THREATENING INJURIES, GREG BURTON DID HAVE SOME LACERATIONS AND BRUSHING AND BOTH DRIVERS WERE TRANSPORTED BY EMS TO LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR CARE. SC STATE PATROL, FIRE, AMBULANCE AND TOWING SERVICES WERE ALL DISPATCHED. HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED FOR REMEDIATION OF APPROXIMATELY 2100-2500 GALLONS OF ETHANOL RELEASED FROM TANKER. TANKER HAD A SMALL HOLE IN FRONT AND REAR COMPARTMENT, DUE TO SAFETY REASONS GOOD PICTURES OF HOLES WERE UNABLE TO BE TAKEN.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY THE FEDEX DRIVER BEING DISTRACTED BY AN ELECTRONIC DEVICE. TEAM LOGISTICS DRIVERS HAVE BEEN ARE TRAINED IN  HAZMAT, SAFE DRIVING WITH SMITH SYSTEM, AND MONTHLY COMPANY TRAINING. TEAM ALSO RUNS HELL TRAILERS THAT HAVE AN EXCELLENT INDUSTRY RATING. AT THIS TIME WE HAVE NO SUGGESTIONS THAT WOULD HAVE CHANGE THE OUT COME OF THIS RELEASE DUE TO TRAINING OR PACKAGING.

column168: AS DRIVER WAS ON HIS WAY TO DELIVER HIS CARGO TO THE CUSTOMER HE SUFFERED A TIRE BLOWOUT THAT CAUSED THE POWER UNIT AND TRAILER TO OVERTURNED. THE LEFT FRONT TIRE BLEW OUT, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO VEER LEFT ACROSS THE ROADWAY. AS THE VEHICLE MOVED LEFT, THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER JACKKNIFED AND ROLLED OVER. A HOLE ABOUT 6 INCHES BY 2 INCHES WAS RIPPED IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE TANKER TRAILER WAS LOST AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. REAGENT CHEMICAL PERSONNEL RESPOND TO THE SITE AND STARTED THE PROCESS TO NEUTRALIZE THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID THAT HAD SPILLED ON THE GROUND. REAGENT CHEMICAL THEN ENGAGED ALLIED INTERNATIONAL EMERGENCY LLC TO CONTINUE THE RESPONSE AND CONDUCT ANY REMEDIATION THAT WAS REQUIRED.
column169: ADDITIONAL DRIVER TRAINING WAS CONDUCTED.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING PROPANE DELIVERIES. IN BETWEEN DELIVERIES, WHILE DRIVING FROM ONE STOP TO THE NEXT, PROPANE BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER SPOKE WITH COMPANY OWNER, PARKED IN SAFEST PLACE POSSIBLE AND CONTACTED 911. DRIVER EVACUATED THE TRUCK AND THE STREET AROUND WHERE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED. POLICE AND EMS BLOCKED THE ROAD AND EVACUATED HOMES CLOSE TO THE TRUCK. POLICE AND EMS CUT POWER TO THE HOMES CLOSE TO THE TRUCK. EMS CONTACTED VIRGINIA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT. VA EMS TOOK OVER THE SCENE AND CONTACTED NN HAZMAT TEAM. WE ATTEMPTED TO PUMP THE TANK BUT WERE UNABLE TO DO SO DUE TO LACK OF PRESSURE IN THE VESSEL. WE RELOCATED THE TRUCK TO AN OPEN AREA APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES AWAY. WE ATTEMPTED TO PUMP THE TANK BUT WERE UNABLE TO DO SO DUE TO LACK OF PRESSURE IN THE VESSEL. WE CONTACTED THE AUTHORIZED SERVICE CENTER WHO HANDLES OUR PROPANE TRUCK INSPECTIONS AND REPAIRS. THEIR MECHANIC CAME TO THE SCENE, REMOVED THE RELIEF VALVE AND PLUGGED THE TOP OF THE TANK. WE DELIVERED THE TRUCK TO THE AUTHORIZED SERVICE CENTER FOR INVESTIGATION AND IT WAS DEEMED THAT THE BAFFLE HIT THE BOTTOM OF THE RELIEF VALVE CAUSING IT TO BLOW APART, RESULTING IN THE LEAK.
column169: INCIDENT WAS UNPREVENTABLE. TRUCK AND TANK HAVE HAD ALL REQUIRED INSPECTIONS.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: THE TRAILER WAS FILLED PROPERLY DURING A NORMAL FILLING SEQUENCE AND THEN PROPERLY DISCONNECTED AND PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT. THE TRAILER SAT FOR 1-3 HOURS BEFORE DEPARTURE. AS NORMAL AND PROPER DURING THIS TIME, THE GAS PRESSURE DECREASED AS THE INTERNAL GAS TEMPERATURE DECREASED. TRAILER WAS EN ROUTE TO XNG'S LITTLE FALLS, NY TERMINAL WHEN THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY AT LATITUDE 42.77069, LONGITUDE -75.028054 ON NY-28 IN EXETER, NY. TRACTOR AND TRAILER ENDED UP ON THEIR SIDE NEXT TO THE ROADWAY. XNG WAS CONTACTED BY LOCAL FIRST RESPONDERS FROM THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE SUSTAINED MINOR INJURIES AND DECLINED TO BE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL. AN XNG ENGINEER AND MANAGEMENT REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED ON SITE APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT. THEY ASSESSED THE CONDITION OF THE TRAILER AND DETERMINED THAT IT WAS LEAKING FROM AN UNDETERMINED POINT NEAR THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE. IN CONSULTATION WITH LOCAL FIRST RESPONDERS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRAILER SHOULD BE VENTED DOWN TO ZERO PRESSURE PRIOR TO RECOVERY. INCLUDING BOTH THE INITIAL LEAK AND THE CONTROLLED RELEASE, APPROXIMATELY 432,000 SCF OF COMPRESSED NATURAL GAS WEIGHING 18,525 POUNDS WERE RELEASED. THE TRAILER WAS HAULED TO A NEARBY DEPOT FACILITY FOR A SAFETY INSPECTION, THEN RELEASED TO XNG.
column169: XNG HAS A COMPREHENSIVE, ONGOING TRAINING PROGRAM FOR ALL COMPANY DRIVERS. WE EMPLOY THE SMITH SYSTEM DRIVER DIRECT COURSES.

column168: OUR DRIVER INDICATED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS TO AVOID A CRASH. TEXAS STATE TROOPER WAS IN THE OUTSIDE LANE OF INTERSTATE 20 WEST APPROXIMATELY 8 CAR LENGTHS IN FRONT OF OUR DRIVER. TRAFFIC WAS TRAVELING ABOUT 65 MPH. TROOPER THEN MADE A SUDDEN MOVE INTO THE INSIDE LANE. THE RESULTING ACTION CAUSED THE CARS IN FRONT OF OUR DRIVERS TO LOCK UP THEIR BRAKES. OUR DRIVER HAD TO BRAKE HARD AND STEER TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID A REAR END ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND THEN ON TO A DIRT SURFACE. THE QUICK MANEUVER AND SUDDEN BRAKING CAUSED THE CARGO STRAPS TO SNAP (USED 4 CARGO STRAPS EACH RATED AT 3350 LBS). THREE OF FOUR IBC CAME OFF THE GOOSE NECK TRAILER. TWO OF THE IBCS RUPTURED AND LEAKED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND MEDIUM. POLICE AND FIRE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. FIRE DEPT HANDLED THE SPILL. NO POLICE REPORT OR FIRE REPORT WERE TAKEN.
column169: ALL FLATBED GOOSE NECK TRAILERS ARE BEING REFITTED WITH ANGLE IRON TO CREATE A TRACK IN WHICH TO STORE IBCS. IN ADDITION, WE'VE ADDED A 3RD STRAP TO THE SECUREMENT OF THE FREIGHT AND ALL REPLACEMENT STRAPS IN SIZE FROM A 2 INCH (WWL OF 3350LBS) TO 3 INCH WIDE WITH A WLL OF 5400 LBS. THE ADDITION OF THE ANGLE IRON AND ADDITIONAL WLL OF STRAPS WILL STOP ANY MOVEMENT OF IBC IN ADVERSE DRIVING CONDITIONS.

column168: ON JULY 13 2018 I, (PERRY HAGUE) DRIVER FOR DAVISON TRANSPORT RECEIVED A MESSAGE TO LOAD 8500 GALS OF 87E10, OUT OF VALERO REFINERY FOR A CUSTOMER LOCATED IN COVINGTON LA. ON ARRIVAL, I WAS ABLE TO ENTER THE ROAD SIDE LOADING RACK INSIDE LANE AND BEGAN THE PROCEDURES TO LOAD THE PRODUCT REQUESTED.  ONCE THE SCULLY, VAPOR HOSE WAS CONNECTED AND THE BELLY VALVES WERE OPEN I ATTACHED THE LOADING ARMS TO THE APPROPRIATE LOAD HEADS, AND WENT TO THE CARD READER AND BEGAN SELECTING THE ACCOUNT. LOAD ARM 5 WAS ATTACHED TO LOAD COMPARTMENT 4 ON THE TANKER AND WAS ACTIVATED AND LOADING WAS CONFIRMED. LOADING ARM 6 WAS ATTACHED TO LOAD COMPARTMENT 2  ON THE TANKER AND WAS ACTIVATED. WHEN I GOT TO LOAD ARM 7, WHICH WAS ATTACHED TO COMPARTMENT 1 (WHICH HAS A 3500 GALLON CAPACITY) I REALIZED IT HAD BEEN DEACTIVATED, SO I DID NOT SELECT, OR ENTER A LOAD AMOUNT INTO THE CARD READER TO LOAD NUMBER 7. IT WAS WHEN I ATTEMPTED TO DETACH LOAD ARM 7 THAT REALIZED THIS WAS NOT POSSIBLE, BECAUSE OF THE POSITION OF LOAD ARM 6, SO DECIDED TO LEAVE IT ON UNTIL LOAD ARM 6 HAD FINISHED LOADING, BUT WHEN I RETURNED TO THE CARD READER I REALIZED THAT EVEN THOUGH I HAD NOT PRESELECTED A COMPARTMENT OR ENTERED AN AMOUNT, OR HIGHLIGHTED LOADING ARM 7, THE READER WAS INDICATING THAT FUEL WAS FLOWING AND THE COMPARTMENT WAS LOADING. I DECIDED TO USE THE STOP PROCEDURE ON THE CARD READER IN AN ATTEMPT TO SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF FUEL SO I COULD DETACH LOAD ARM 6 AND THEN ARM 7 TO CORRECT THIS. ARMS 5 AND 6 STOPPED IMMEDIATELY, BUT LOAD ARM 7 CONTINUED TO FLOW, AND ONCE THE READER INDICATED JUST OVER 2200 GALLONS, GASOLINE BEGAN TO SPEW OUT OF THE TOP HATCH OF COMPARTMENT 1, (WHICH HAS A 3500 GALLON CAPACITY). THE ESD (EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN DEVICE) WAS ACTIVATED SHORTLY AFTER, STOPPING THE FLOW OF FUEL TO ALL ARMS ON ALL LOAD RACKS. ALL FUEL WAS CONTAINED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE RACK, AND NO FUEL, THAT I SAW EVER REACHED ANY AREAS OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT. I LATER FOUND, AN OPERATOR THAT WORKS AT THE TERMINAL LOADING RACK WAS WORKING ON THE LOADING ARM, (7) DISABLED IT BUT DIDN'T TAG OR LOCKOUT THE ARM THAT CREATED THE SPILL. THIS IS, TO MY BEST RECOLLECTION OF THE EVENTS WHAT HAPPENED ON THE DAY IN QUESTION.  SIGNED PERRY HAGUE DAVISON TRANSPORT LOUISIANA TERMINAL

column168: THE DRIVER PULLED INTO GRAPEVINE SCALE OF WHICH TIME TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE SCALE PERSONNEL GUIDED HIM TO AN AREA. KERN COUNTY HEALTH & SAFETY VEHICLE WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THEY BEGAN SECURING THE AREA. THE DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH OF WHICH PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY. PATRIOT WORKED WITH THE DIRECTION OF KERN COUNTY PERSONNEL AND CA. SCALE OPERATIONS. THE AREA WAS SECURED NEUTRALIZED, AND CLEAN UP BEGAN. IT WAS FOUND THAT A SHARP OBJECT CAUSED A SMALL HOLE ON THE IBC TOTE. THE ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY STOPPED THE LEAK FROM THE IBC TOTE THE TOTE WHICH WAS APPROX 20 FEET FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS FULL WITH VARIOUS LTL SHIPMENTS. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 4 TOTAL IBC TOTES. 1 TOTE WAS LEAKING AND THE BALANCE OF PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO 3 - POLY 55 GALLON DRUMS. THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA WAS EXPERIENCING A HEAT WAVE WITH EXTREMELY HIGH TEMPERATURE. THIS FACTOR ADDED TO THE TIME FRAME OF THE OPERATION FOR ALL INVOLVED.  THIS WAS AN UNUSUAL OCCURRENCE.
column169: THE OCCURRENCE WAS DISCUSSED IN A MEETING. WE HAVE ADDED ADDITIONAL VISUAL INFORMATION ADDRESSING THESE ISSUES FOR PRESENT AND FUTURE EMPLOYEES. OUR COMPANY HAS INVESTED IN VISUAL STICKERS WARNING OF LIQUID PRODUCTS IN TRAILERS. THIS PROCESS IS ADDITION TO OUR TRAINING MANUALS. THIS IS A WARNING TO EMPLOYEE OF THE IMPORTANCE OF HANDLING LIQUID. THESE WERE DISTRIBUTED TO OUR OPERATION DEPOTS IN THE LAST FEW WEEKS.

column168: TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON BRITTON RD, 1/2 MILE EAST OF BANNER ROAD BETWEEN EL RENO AND YUKON, OK. DRIVER WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 47 MPH WHEN HE TOOK HIS EYES OF THE ROAD INTERMITTENTLY CAUSING HIM TO VEER LEFT AND THEN RIGHT OFF THE ROADWAY. ONCE THE TRANSPORT'S PASSENGER SIDE WHEELS LEFT THE ROADWAY, THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO BRING IT BACK ON THE ROAD, BUT THE WEIGHT OF THE LOADED TRAILER TOOK OVER AND THE TRANSPORT OVERTURNED. THE TRANSPORT CAME TO REST ON IT'S DRIVERS SIDE WITH THE TRAILER ON THE RIGHT-AWAY AND THE TRACTOR LAYING ACROSS THE EASTBOUND LANE. THE DRIVER SUSTAINED NON LIFE-THREATENING INJURIES AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO MERCY HOSPITAL VIA AMBULANCE. THE CARGO TANK DID NOT BREACH, BUT SOME FUEL WAS LOST DUE TO LEAKING MAN-WAY HATCH GASKETS. EMERGENCY SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE INCLUDING OK HIGHWAY PATROL, FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND OK DEQ. PTI DISPATCHED A RESPONSE TEAM, WRECKER SERVICE, AND HAZMAT CREW. THE FUEL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRUCK AND THE WRECKER SERVICE UPRIGHT WRECKED TRANSPORT AND TOWED IT TO THE PTL'S OKC YARD. THE ROADWAY WAS REOPENED AT 21:30 PM. THE INCIDENT RESPONSE REPORT BY CLEANUP CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT IS ATTACHED.
column169: AN INCIDENT REVIEW BOARD WAS HELD TO INVESTIGATE AND UNDERSTAND THE ROLLOVER INCIDENT. ADDITIONAL DRIVER TRAINING AND AWARENESS WERE INCREASED IN THE DISTRICT TO REDUCE RECURRENCE. OTHER ACTION ITEMS INCLUDED: REDEFINING ACTIONS FOR GETTING DRIVERS SPECIFIC DIRECTIONS TO JOB LOCATIONS, REVIEWING CELL PHONE POLICY WITH ALL DRIVERS, AND RESEARCHING/IMPLEMENTING COMMERCIAL TRUCK NAVIGATION SOFTWARE.

column168: DRIVER WAS ON THE SOUTHBOUND 101 NEAR THE MADONNA EXIT IN SAN LUIS OBISPO AT 3:00 P.M. ON JULY 27, 2018, THE DAY WAS CLEAR AND SUNNY. DRIVING ON THE 101 AND OTHER DRIVERS WERE EXITING AND ENTERING OFF AND ON RAMPS, DRIVER OF DOT VEHICLE DRIVING TRUCK/TRAILER WITH LOADED POTASSIUM NITRATE. TRAFFIC WAS VERY CONGESTED, DRIVER OF DOT VEHICLE CAME TO A SUDDEN STOP TO PREVENT COLLISION CAUSING THE LOAD ON TRAILER TO SHIFT. PRODUCT THAT WAS SHIFTED FORCED 17 BAGS TO SHIFT AND FORCE OFF OF TWO PALLETS ONTO THE 101 ROAD. DRIVER WAS MOVING VEHICLE OFF TO THE RIGHT SIDE TO MOVE OUT OF THE TRAFFIC, AN EMPLOYEE OF GUGGIA TRUCKING ARRIVED APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES LATER, 3:15 P.M. TO ASSIST WITH PICKING UP THE BAGS THAT WERE ON THE 101 ROAD. THAT EMPLOYEE COLLECTED 2 BAGS, THE BALANCE OF 14 BAGS DID NOT GET PICKED. HIGHWAY PATROL ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER HIGHWAY PATROL WITH 2 PICKUP TRUCKS/3 CAL TRANS EMPLOYEES. CAL TRANS 3 EMPLOYEES SCOOPED PRODUCT WITH PLASTIC SHOVEL AND TRANSFERRED PRODUCT INTO THEIR ORANGE BAGS, ABOUT 3 BAGS; APPROXIMATELY 30 LBS. EACH. SHORTLY  AFTER THE CAL TRANS WORKERS COLLECTED THE PRODUCT, THE CAL TRANS SWEEPER CAME INTO SWEEP THE AREA 2 TIMES. THE HIGHWAY PATROL INTERVIEWED THE DRIVER FOR ABOUT 10 MINUTES, ISSUED A COLLISION REPORT INFORMATION NCIC 9745.
column169: IMPROVEMENT TO INCLUDE A HEADBOARD AND CROSS TRIES ON THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. CIEP TRAINING CONDUCTED ON A QUARTERLY SCHEDULE TO REVIEW PRE-TIP, ROAD HAZARD AWARENESS, HOURS OF SERVICE, DRIVER FITNESS, HAZMAT, AND LOAD SECUREMENT. MONTHLY SAFETY TRAINING REGARDING RULES OF THE ROAD, PERSONAL SAFETY, AND PUBLIC SAFETY WHILE IN TRANSIT: NO TEXTING WHILE DRIVING OR HOLDING PHONE WHILE DRIVING, MINIMIZE TIME ON CELL PHONE TO CONCENTRATE ON DRIVING AND HAZARDS.
